# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: major-league-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The building's eight-story base partially wraps around its 48-story main tower.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Both sections are surrounded by a plaza, which has white-and-gray pavement in a serpentine pattern, as well as water fountains.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The facade consists of glass panels between limestone columns.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The lobby contains serpentine floors, white-marble and stainless-steel walls, and reddish-burgundy glass ceilings, in addition to artwork by Josef Albers, Fritz Glarner, and Francis Brennan.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The ground floor also includes storefronts and originally housed La Fonda del Sol, a Latin American–themed restaurant.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Each of the upper floors covers 28,000 square feet (2,600 m2), with the offices arranged around the core.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The 48th floor originally contained the Hemisphere Club, which operated as a members-only restaurant during the day and was open to the public during evenings.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] After the media firm Time Inc. expressed its intention to move from 1 Rockefeller Plaza in the 1950s, Rockefeller Center's owners proposed a skyscraper at 1271 Avenue of the Americas to accommodate the move.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Construction started in May 1957; the building was topped out during November 1958, and occupants began moving into their offices in late 1959.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission designated the lobby as a city landmark in 2002.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Time Inc. vacated 1271 Avenue of the Americas in 2015, and the building was subsequently renovated between 2015 and 2019.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] 1271 Avenue of the Americas is on the western side of Sixth Avenue (officially Avenue of the Americas), between 50th and 51st streets, in the Midtown Manhattan neighborhood of New York City.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The land lot is rectangular and covers 82,340 square feet (7,650 m2).
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The site has a frontage of 410 feet (120 m) on 50th and 51st streets and a frontage of 200 feet (61 m) on Sixth Avenue.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Nearby buildings include The Michelangelo to the west, Axa Equitable Center to the northwest, 75 Rockefeller Plaza to the northeast, Radio City Music Hall to the east, 30 Rockefeller Plaza to the southeast, and 1251 Avenue of the Americas to the south.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Prior to the development of 1271 Avenue of the Americas, much of the site had previously served as a New York Railways Company trolley barn, which in turn was replaced by a parking lot.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] There was also a four-story building facing Sixth Avenue and a collection of single-story shops on 50th Street.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Rockefeller Center Inc. bought the plots on 50th and 51st streets in the first week of August 1953, followed by those on Sixth Avenue the next week.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] One building on the site reportedly cost $2 million after its owner had held out.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Rockefeller Center's managers originally wanted to build an NBC studio or a Ford vehicle showroom on the site.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The building was designed by Harrison & Abramovitz, a firm led by Wallace Harrison and Max Abramovitz.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] It was constructed by John Lowry and the George A.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Syska Hennessy was hired as the mechanical engineering firm, and Edwards & Hjorth was the structural engineering firm.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] 1271 Avenue of the Americas was planned as a 48-story tower, rising 587 feet (179 m) and measuring around 310 by 104 feet (94 by 32 m).
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The tower is flanked by shorter segments with setbacks at the third and eighth stories.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The north and west edges of the tower are flanked by a seven-story section of the base.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] An auditorium designed by Gio Ponti, with colored triangles, was installed on the eighth-floor setback.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The neighboring Roxy Theatre was acquired as part of the building's development, allowing the building's floor area to be increased under the limits set by the 1916 Zoning Resolution.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] A provision under the 1916 Zoning Resolution had allowed structures to rise without setbacks above a given level if all subsequent stories covered no more than 25 percent of the land lot.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] 1271 Avenue of the Americas' facade is made mostly of glass, which at the time of the building's construction cost the same as a wall made mostly of limestone.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The use of a glass facade permitted a higher degree of flexibility on each story compared to a limestone wall of the same size.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Before the current facade design was selected, several alternatives were considered.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Time Inc. wanted a flush exterior wall, but this was rejected because exterior columns would protrude into the floor area.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Another alternative called for an accordion-shaped wall: The windows would have sloped inward, and the spandrel panels between the windows on each story would have sloped outward.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The accordion wall, which would have been framed by flat columns, was infeasible because it reduced floor area, required modifications to the drapes and air-conditioning, and was not aesthetically desirable to the architects.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] At ground level, there is a canopy over the 51st Street entrance.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The rest of the tower has a glass curtain wall.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] On all stories, the facade includes structural columns with limestone cladding.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The limestone columns frame the glass curtain wall and also serve as an architectural allusion to the other buildings at Rockefeller Center.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] In addition, more than 40,000 feet (12,000 m) of stainless-steel flashing was placed on the facade.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The stainless-steel flashing was meant to last for as long as the building existed; on the setbacks at the base, the flashing was buried inside corners along the roof deck.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The limestone columns are spaced every 28 feet (8.5 m).
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] There are five vertical bays of windows between each set of limestone columns.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Each bay has two narrow aluminum mullions flanking the center pane and two larger air-conditioning risers along the outer panes.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Originally, each glass pane measured 52 inches (1,300 mm) wide and 56 inches (1,400 mm) tall.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The spandrels between the windows on different stories consist of a 0.25-inch-thick (6.4 mm) plate, behind which is a screen made of aluminum mesh.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The mechanical pipes and ducts, as well as the floor slabs, are hidden behind the spandrels.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The windows were planned as square panes, but the window sills were lowered during the design process so they were only 2.5 feet (0.76 m) above each floor slab.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Each spandrel was then covered by a regular glass pane.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] In the late 2010s, new low-emissivity glazed panels with thermal breaks were installed.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The eastern part of the site was planned with a plaza.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The plaza measures 170 feet (52 m) long and 83 feet (25 m) wide and is flanked by the eight-story base.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The southern part of the site also has a promenade that is about 30 feet (9.1 m) wide.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The plaza has pavers in a serpentine pattern, similar to those found on the sidewalks of Rio de Janeiro's Copacabana Beach.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] According to the architectural writer Robert A.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Stern, the pavement was "an illustration of the 'good neighbor' ideals of the Avenue of the Americas Association".
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Harrison believed the pavers would bring variety to the building's design.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The original pavers, designed by Port Morris Tile & Marble Corporation, were removed in 2001 because they were too slippery; the same company reproduced the pattern in rougher terrazzo.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] In the late 2010s, the sidewalk pattern was extended from the lot line to the curb line.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] A seating parapet in the plaza surrounded a reflecting pool with four jets, measuring about 110 by 30 feet (33.5 by 9.1 m).
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Another six pools, measuring 33.5 by 6 feet (10.2 by 1.8 m) each, were placed within the plaza.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Each pool had a mat made of lead for waterproofing, which in turn was covered by cement and terrazzo.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Trees and shrubs were originally also planted on the 50th Street side, while three flagpoles were placed on the section of the plaza facing Sixth Avenue.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] After the late 2010s renovation, the original decorations were replaced.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The new decorations included five pools with fountain jets on Sixth Avenue, in addition to planting beds and seating areas.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Also within the plaza is an entrance to the New York City Subway's 47th–50th Streets–Rockefeller Center station, serving the B, D, F, <F>, and M trains.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] In 1972, the Association for a Better New York hired William Crovello to create a sculpture at the building called *Cubed Curve*, measuring 8 feet (2.4 m) wide and 12 feet (3.7 m) wide.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The sculpture was inspired by a fluid brush stroke.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] According to *The New York Times*, the sculpture marked Time Inc.'s "presence at the center of the media universe".
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] It was moved in 2018 to Ursinus College in Collegeville, Pennsylvania, while the building was being renovated.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] 1271 Avenue of the Americas was built with about 1,400,000 square feet (130,000 m2) of rentable space.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] According to the New York City Department of City Planning, the building has a gross floor area of 1,962,900 square feet (182,360 m2).
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The interior design was contracted to a variety of architects, including Alexander Girard, Gio Ponti, Charles Eames, William Tabler, and George Nelson & Company.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Thirty elevators, within the core, serve the building.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The building's interior is divided into eight air-conditioning zones.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Floors 8, 9, and 16 through 34 were originally occupied by Time Inc. and had their own thermostats, accommodating the nonstandard working hours of Time Inc. employees.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] In conjunction with the building's construction, Rockefeller Center's central air-conditioning system was upgraded in 1957 to provide 6,000 tons of cooling capacity to the building every hour.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The cooling systems had to operate all year because Time Inc.'s equipment generated large amounts of heat.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The original cooling system was powered by steam, but electric and natural gas cooling systems had been added by 2000.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The mechanical spaces are concealed by narrow windows on the facade.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The first basement has a passageway leading to Rockefeller Center's underground concourse and the 47th–50th Streets–Rockefeller Center station.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The two other basements are not accessible to the public and are used for storage, maintenance, and service functions.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] 1271 Avenue of the Americas' lobby is surrounded by commercial spaces on all sides; with the superstructure incorporated in the core and exterior, Harrison could design the lobby with more flexibility.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Originally, the lobby was planned to include a covered shopping and exhibit hall on 50th Street and a north–south passage between 50th and 51st streets.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] These details were changed significantly in the final plan.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The lobby has two entrances to the south on 50th Street, one on either side of the core, as well as an entrance to the north on 51st Street, along the east side of the core.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The core itself has two west–east passages connected by elevator banks.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The more northerly of the east–west passages has stairs and escalators to the second story and the basement.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Until the 1990s, the southern passage had been a narrow hallway because there were two storefronts next to it.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] A breezeway led east to Sixth Avenue, but this had been closed by 2002.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Time Inc.'s reception area was within the lobby behind the fountain.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The lobby has the same style of pavement as the plaza outside the building.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The original tiles were installed by the American Mosaic & Tile Company.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] They were made of white cementitious terrazzo with stainless steel borders, aligned west–east.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The southern section of the lobby was expanded in the 1990s, over the site of the storefronts there, but the extended floor did not match the original pavement.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The entire lobby was resurfaced in the late 2010s with marble-based terrazzo tiles that matched the original floor design.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Because the marble tiles had contained natural veins of black rock, contractors manually removed the veins before installing the tiles.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The walls are largely made of plate-glass windows and white marble panels.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Around the core, the walls are made of stainless steel rectangular panels.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The steel panels are designed to complement the floor colors and are arranged in a checkerboard pattern.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The ceiling throughout the lobby is 16 feet (4.9 m) high and was originally made of dark maroon glass tiles, finished in a matte covering.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] There were white lighting coves in some tiles.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Manufactured by American-Saint Gobain Corporation, the glass tiles were suspended from washers at each corner and were designed to be removed for maintenance.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] In the late 2010s, the original glass ceiling was replaced with reddish-burgundy tiles of similar design, which matched the original color.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The lobby walls contain large murals by Josef Albers and Fritz Glarner, both of whom Harrison had known for many years.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Glarner's mural, entitled *Relational Painting No.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] 88,* measures 40 by 15 feet (12.2 by 4.6 m) and is mounted east of the elevators.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] It includes overlapping red, yellow, blue, gray, and black geometric shapes on a white background.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Albers's mural, entitled *Portals,* measures 42 by 14 feet (12.8 by 4.3 m) and is mounted west of the elevators.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] *Portals* includes alternating bands of white and brown glass, which surround a set of bronze and nickel plates in a way that gives the impression of depth.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] 88* was installed in April 1960, while *Portals* was installed twelve months later.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Another artwork by *Fortune* art director Francis Brennan was installed north of the elevators in January 1965.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Brennan's work consists of a relief measuring 13 by 6 feet (4.0 by 1.8 m), which contains all the letters of the alphabet in the Caslon 471 typeface.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] When 1271 Avenue of the Americas opened, there was a Manufacturers Trust bank branch within the northeast corner of the base, next to the lobby.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] There had also been two storefronts along the southern end of the lobby, next to the west–east corridor there, but the storefronts were removed in the 1990s.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Along the lobby's west side was La Fonda del Sol (the Inn of the Sun), a Latin American–themed restaurant operated by Joseph Baum of Restaurant Associates.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The interiors were designed by Alexander Girard and furniture by Charles Eames.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] La Fonda had an elaborate entry foyer and a set of dining spaces leading to the largest dining room.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The dining rooms were decorated with Latin American artifacts, and each of the dining rooms was furnished in vivid colors with at least two hues of fabrics.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] It relocated elsewhere in 1971 and was replaced with a bank branch.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Originally used by the Seaman's Bank for Savings, the branch had round steel columns as well as green marble counters with flecks of white.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] As of 2021, the businesses in the lobby include the Capital Grille and Ted's Montana Grill.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The seven lowest stories each have about 62,000 square feet (5,800 m2) of floor space.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Each of the upper stories has around 28,000 square feet (2,600 m2), largely uninterrupted by columns.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] These were among the largest floor slabs of any office building in New York City since World War II.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] All stairs and elevators are placed in the core, leaving the outer section of each floor available for use.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] This improved the efficiency of each floor by allowing an open plan for the offices.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The arrangement of the building allowed high flexibility in planning interior offices.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] An office module in the building generally measured 48 by 56 inches (1.2 by 1.4 m), though these could be combined as necessary.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The interior arrangement was inspired by that of the PSFS Building in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The firm Designs for Business was responsible for the design of Time Inc.'s space, which originally spanned 21 stories.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Time Inc. had to fit multiple small rooms and cubicles on each of its floors, but the company was largely able to fit these rooms and cubicles within the modular system.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Square aluminum posts were installed in Time Inc.'s space, through which partition panels could be installed.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The panels were made of a myriad of materials including wood, plastic, burlap, and glass, though they were initially not soundproof.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Mockups of the offices were manufactured at Astoria, Queens, as well as in Time Inc.'s earlier headquarters at 1 Rockefeller Plaza.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The elevator lobbies on each of Time Inc.'s stories had different decorations.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The 28th floor also had a photo gallery where photojournalist Alfred Eisenstaedt worked.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] After Charles Eames designed the chairs for Time Inc.'s offices, he created a new chair design in 1961, which was nicknamed the Time-Life Chair.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Eames designed them as a favor to Henry Luce, the founder of *Time* and *Life* magazines, who had allowed Eames to use photos from the Time-Life archives for the pavilion he designed at the 1959 American National Exhibition in Moscow.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The chairs remain in production during the 21st century, albeit with modifications for stability and to meet updated product codes.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Other offices in the building originally included the second-story offices of the Gilman Paper Company, designed by SLS-Environetics and connected to the lobby by an escalator.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The vestibule at the top of the escalators had stainless-steel wall and a carpet that extended across the floor and part of the walls.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Gilman's reception area had an angular reception desk and lighting fixtures made of stainless steel.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Gilman's offices had ceilings measuring 13 feet (4.0 m) tall, with angular furniture, sculpted ducts and lighting elements, exposed structural beams, and a color-coding scheme to distinguish the different departments.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The Rockefeller Group also has an office on the 24th floor, which was redesigned in 2020 by the firm of Fogarty Finger.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The Rockefeller Group's offices include a reception area with dark woods and a pantry designed in a mid-century modern style.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] There are open plan workspaces with dropped ceilings, as well as executive offices and meeting spaces with glass walls.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Gio Ponti designed an auditorium at the setback above the eighth floor, along with an adjoining kitchen, dining room, reception area, and lounge.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] This space was meant for meetings with advertisers and corporate and sales functions.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The space was arranged with walls at irregular angles and originally had colored glass-block walls and Sicilian paintings.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The auditorium itself had a domed ceiling, while the ceiling in the adjoining spaces contained brass motifs.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The floors were yellow with green and blue streaks, and geometric wooden furniture was specially designed for the space.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The auditorium was closed by 1981, and the furniture was sold.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] It was redesigned by Davis, Brody & Associates in 1983 and became a conference center.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The Hemisphere Club and Tower Suite shared a space on the 48th floor, which was designed by George Nelson & Company.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] During the day, the Hemisphere Club was a 250-seat private club for executives that, when the building opened, charged $1,000 for initiation and $360 in annual fees thereafter.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] This made the Hemisphere Club one of several private clubs at the tops of New York City skyscrapers.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] In the evenings, the restaurant space opened to the public as the Tower Suite, which originally offered meals for $8.50 per person.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The restaurant was operated by Restaurant Associates.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] George Nelson designed special chairs for the restaurant, which apparently were never manufactured.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Since the windows split the view from the 48th floor into many sections, the space was designed with window embrasures.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The media firm Time Inc. had been housed at 1 Rockefeller Plaza since 1937, when that building had opened as part of the construction of Rockefeller Center.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] As early as 1946, it had sought to develop the site of the Hotel Marguery at 270 Park Avenue for a 35-story headquarters designed by Harrison & Abramovitz, though the plans did not come to fruition.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] By 1953, Time Inc. was set to outgrow its existing space in 1 Rockefeller Plaza within a year, and it wanted to have its headquarters in a single building.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Time Inc. seriously considered relocating to Westchester County, a northern suburb of New York City, as well as to a suburb of Philadelphia.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] By November 1955, the company had decided to stay in New York City because of the large number of transportation options there.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Once Rockefeller Center Inc.'s managers learned of Time Inc.'s predicament, they hired Harrison & Abramovitz to create plans for a building on Rockefeller Center Inc.'s vacant plot that could house both NBC and Time.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The plans involved creating several elevation drawings as well as a 15-minute film.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] NBC ultimately dropped out of the project because its CEO, David Sarnoff, dissented.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Rockefeller Center Inc. acquired the Roxy Theater in August 1956.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] That December, officials announced the construction of the Time-Life Building.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] When the plans were announced, Time had leased 600,000 square feet (56,000 m2) in the building, and American Cyanamid, Shell Oil Company, McCann-Erickson, and Esso had already made lease agreements for other floors.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The developers had already ordered 27,000 tons of structural steel to be delivered in early 1958.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Time Inc. and Rockefeller Center Inc. formed a joint venture, Rock-Time Inc., to share the tower's rental income.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Rockefeller Center had the majority stake of 55 percent, and Time Inc. had the remaining 45 percent.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Harrison & Abramovitz filed plans for the building in March 1957.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] A groundbreaking ceremony occurred on May 16, 1957, marking the start of excavation.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] By the following month, the building was 70 percent leased, and Curtiss-Wright and Westinghouse Electric Corporation had become tenants.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The Rockefeller Center Sidewalk Superintendents' Club, composed of members of the public who wanted to observe Rockefeller Center's construction, was revived after having been dormant for seventeen years.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The actress Marilyn Monroe presided over the club's inaugural ceremonies that July.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The site was excavated to a depth of 40 feet (12 m), where there was a layer of Manhattan schist.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] By November 1957, the excavations were largely complete; the Rockefeller Foundation had leased offices and two tenants had expanded their lease commitments.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Rockefeller Center Inc. chairman Nelson Rockefeller and Time Inc. president Roy E.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Larsen announced details of the design the same month.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Construction on the Time-Life Building's superstructure started in April 1958.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] That August, the Equitable Life Assurance Society lent the project's developers $50 million.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] At the time, it was the largest-ever financing on a single real-estate parcel.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The structure topped out in November of that year.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The next April, Time Inc. sublet six of the 21 floors under its control.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The building was 92 percent leased by then, including the space that was being sublet.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The Time-Life Building's cornerstone was laid in June 1959, at the southeast corner of the building, after the superstructure had been completed.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The first tenant, the American Cyanamid Company, began moving into the tower in October 1959.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Over the next couple of months, tenants began moving into the building and the final interior design elements were installed.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] By that December, the construction fence around 1271 Avenue of the Americas had been dismantled and several companies had occupied their space.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Additional leases were announced in January 1960, including one storefront.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] A passageway from the basement to the subway station opened the next month.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] *Life* magazine moved into the building that April, writing that its new headquarters was "a victory in the fight to improve down-at-the-heels Sixth Avenue".
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Ultimately, Time Inc. was able to sublet part of its space to more than forty firms.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] By late 1961, the building was almost completely occupied.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] La Fonda del Sol had moved out of the Time & Life Building to a smaller location by early 1971.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The restaurant space was replaced by a Seaman's Trust bank branch.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The bank was so popular that, in three weeks, it performed six months' worth of transactions.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Although *Life* magazine stopped publishing in 1972, the building retained its name, and the former *Life* space was quickly taken by the company's other publications, such as *People* and *Money*.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Steakhouse restaurant designed by Gwathmey Siegel & Associates Architects opened in the building in 1975 and was slightly renovated a few years later.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] By 1981, Time Inc. occupied about 1,000,000 square feet (93,000 m2) of space and some of its divisions, such as HBO, had to be housed in other buildings.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The eighth-floor auditorium was renovated in 1983.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] An electric cooling system was also added in the early 1980s to supplement the original steam-powered cooling system.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Time Inc. sold its 45 percent ownership stake in December 1986 to the Rockefeller Group for $118 million.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Time Inc. planned to use some of the proceeds from the sale for other purchases such as stock buybacks.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] In the same transaction, Time Inc. extended its lease from 1997 to 2007, with an option to extend its lease by another ten years, to 2017.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Time Inc. executed its option to extend its lease in 1999.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] At the time, the company occupied 80 percent of the Time & Life Building and it had rented space at the adjacent 135 West 50th Street.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The two buildings were to be connected internally on the second floor as part of a $190 million renovation.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] A natural-gas cooling system was added in 2000; at the time, it was New York City's only building with three cooling sources.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] By August 2001, Time Inc. was part of AOL Time Warner and occupied 98 percent of the building's space.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] That month, AOL Time Warner subsidiary CNN and the Rockefeller Group agreed to convert a former Chase Manhattan Bank branch at the base into a two-story CNN television studio.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] In July 2002, the New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission designated the lobby interior as a city landmark.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Municipal Art Society executive director Frank E.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Sanchis III prompted the Rockefeller Group to support the preservation of the lobby.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] At the time, the lobby was being renovated by Swanke Hayden Connell Architects for $40 million.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The renovation involved combining two storefronts into a waiting lounge, as well as creating a secure area around the elevators.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The CNN studio opened in September 2002, with scenic design by Production Design Group.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The Ted's Montana Grill restaurant opened in 2006 on the ground level.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] In May 2014, Time Inc. announced it was planning to leave the Time & Life Building for the Brookfield Place complex in lower Manhattan.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The following year, Time Inc. moved out of its offices, and the Rockefeller Group announced a $325 million renovation of the entire building, designed by Pei Cobb Freed & Partners.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] As part of the renovation, the architects created a new entrance on Sixth Avenue, repaved the plaza, and replaced the facade.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] All 30 elevator cabs were replaced with new cabs whose ceiling design was an homage to the 51st Street canopy.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The Rockefeller Group also restored the lobby and renamed the building to its address.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Time Inc. removed a time capsule that had been embedded in the building when its cornerstone was laid.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The time capsule included contemporary objects such as magazines, photography books, a pencil, and a microfilm about the Rockefeller Center complex.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Glarner's and Albers's paintings were restored, and the floors, ceilings, and signs were modified to match the original design.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The building was completely vacant by the beginning of 2018.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The renovation was nearly completed by 2019, and the building was fully leased at that time.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The building's major tenants included financial firms such as American International Group, Greenhill & Co., and H.I.G.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The other tenants included law firms Blank Rome and Latham & Watkins, as well as multi-family office Bessemer Trust on the top seven floors.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] In addition, Major League Baseball moved its headquarters to the building, and it leased two stories in the building's base for use as an MLB store, which opened in 2020.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] With the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic in New York City, the building stood largely empty for several months in 2020.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The building received a Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) Gold certification the same year.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The building was again fully leased by May 2021, and the Greek restaurant Avra Estiatorio leased a two-story space at the base, which opened in June 2022.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Another restaurant, Cuerno New York, opened in the building in 2025.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Huxtable also characterized 1271 Avenue of the Americas' spaces as "flexible architectural anarchy".
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Horsley, praised the lobby's design and materials, though he believed the facade had an inconspicuous, albeit "not terrible", design.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The Time & Life Building's completion spurred the construction of similar office buildings along Sixth Avenue.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] Stern wrote in his 1995 book *New York 1960* that the building "marked the first key step" in the avenue's reconstruction.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] *Architectural Forum* wrote that the building's completion "opens a wide frontier for an expanding city", leading the way for the construction of other large office buildings west of Sixth Avenue.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] 1271 Avenue of the Americas has appeared in several media works.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The building was featured in the television series *Mad Men* as the fictional headquarters of the advertising agency Sterling Cooper Draper Pryce (later Sterling Cooper & Partners).
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] AMC, the network on which *Mad Men* airs, unveiled a bench in front of the building in 2015; it contains a sculpture of lead character Don Draper's black silhouette, as shown in the show's opening credits.
[src:major-league-baseball/1271-avenue-of-the-americas] The 2013 film *The Secret Life of Walter Mitty* was partially set within the building.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The **1876 major league baseball season** was contested from April 22 through October 21, 1876, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the inaugural season of the National League and of Major League baseball.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Two non-NA teams would join as charter members, including the Cincinnati Reds (unrelated to the modern team) and Louisville Grays.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The 1876 schedule was formatted so that each team would play up to 10 games against each team in the league (split evenly between home and away games), for a maximum of 70 games (only fulfilled by the Boston Red Caps).
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Any game played against a team at home must be played within two months' time away, "under penalty of forfeiture." This was the only season that the National League adopted this format.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see a more regulated format, requiring teams to schedule 12 games against each team.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 22 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Athletics of Philadelphia.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 21, featuring a game between the Hartford Dark Blues and Boston Red Caps.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The first doubleheader in major league history occurred on September 9 between the Cincinnati Reds and Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The year ended with the first postseason competition in major league history.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The contest featured the first and second-place regular season finishers.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Three tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Grays had three tie games.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues, New York Mutuals, and Philadelphia Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues would play their final game at the Hartford Ball Club Grounds on September 16 against the St.
[src:major-league-baseball/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings, relocating to Brooklyn, New York at the Union Grounds as the Brooklyn Hartfords for the start of the 1877 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The **1877 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through October 6, 1877, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the second season of the National League.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1876, two teams were formally kicked out of the league for failing to fulfill their schedules: New York Mutuals and Philadelphia Athletics, contracting the league from eight to six teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blue would relocate from Hartford, Connecticut to Brooklyn, New York, as the Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The 1877 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other five teams in the league.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season that the National League adopted the format.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The format would last only through the following season.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 6, featuring four teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords had two tie games.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Louisville Grays had one tie game each.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings would play their final game at 23rd Street Grounds on October 6 against the Louisville Grays, moving to Lakefront Park for the start of the 1878 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game against the Chicago White Stockings on their last home game of the season, September 22, at the site of the former National Association's New Haven Elm Citys, at the Howard Avenue Grounds in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The **1878 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1878, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the third season of the National League.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1877, two teams would fold: Brooklyn Hartfords and St.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] They were replaced by the Indianapolis Blues and Milwaukee Grays.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Later in the offseason, the Providence Grays would join on February 6, raising the number of teams to seven.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] On April 1 or 2, the Louisville Grays would officially resign from the league, once again lowering the number of teams to six.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The 1878 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] This format had been in place since the previous season, and would be the final season which saw this format, due to expansion to eight teams the following season.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all six teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Two teams hosted games at neutral sites, the Indianapolis Blues and Providence Grays.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Four tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Blues had three tie games.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Milwaukee Grays had one tie game each.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:major-league-baseball/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings leave the 23rd Street Grounds (where they played for four seasons since their National Association days from 1874) and move to Lakefront Park where they would play for seven seasons through 1884.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The **1879 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1879, and saw the Providence Grays as the pennant winner of the fourth season of the National League.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the National League was set on expanding from a six-team league to an eight-team league.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Blues and Milwaukee Grays folded, and in its place, the league admitted the Cleveland Blues, the International Association's Buffalo Bisons and Syracuse Stars, and finally (with confirmation Milwaukee was not returning) the Troy Trojans.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] It is suggested by Society for American Baseball Research (SABR) that this season featured the first African-American to play major league baseball, William Edward White, who played one game with the Providence Grays on June 21.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] He predates brothers Moses Fleetwood Walker and Weldy Walker by five years, and Jackie Robinson by 68 years.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The 1879 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] This format was an adjustment to the 12-games-each format that had been in place since 1877, as the National League expanded from six to eight teams, adding 24 games to each team's schedule.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring six teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Five tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings had four tie games.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons, Cincinnati Reds, Providence Grays, and Syracuse Stars had one tie game each.
[src:major-league-baseball/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans would play their final game at the Putnam Grounds on September 20 against the Chicago White Stockings, moving to Haymakers' Grounds for the start of the 1880 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The **1880 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 1, 1880, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the fifth season of the National League.
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The 1880 season is known for the first two major league perfect games in history, as well as being the only perfect games in the 19th century.
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Thrown by Lee Richmond and John Ward, these two perfect games were thrown in the span of five days, the shortest amount of time between two perfect games (the next closest is currently 20 days between Dallas Braden's May 9 and Roy Halladay's and May 29, 2010 perfect games).
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] A perfect game would not be seen again in the Major Leagues for 24 years when Cy Young threw his perfect game in 1904.
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the Cincinnati Reds and Syracuse Stars disbanded, and were replaced by the Cincinnati Stars and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the Stars' only major league season.
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The 1880 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the previous season and would be used until 1883.
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 1, featuring a doubleheader between the Providence Grays and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Eight tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons, Cincinnati Stars, and Providence Grays had three tie games each.
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, and Worcester Worcesters had two tie games each.
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave the Putnam Grounds (where they played their inaugural seasons) and move to the Haymakers' Grounds, where they would play for two seasons through 1881.
[src:major-league-baseball/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans begin to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing on September 11.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The **1881 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through September 30, 1881, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the sixth season of the National League.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The 1881 season is most known for featuring the first major league grand slam.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Roger Connor of the Troy Trojans hit the walk-off home run at Riverside Park (Greenbush) against the Worcester Worcesters on September 10, leading to an 8–7 victory.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the National League dropped the Cincinnati Stars because the team refused to sign a league pledge that banned alcohol in league parks and forbade clubs from renting their parks out on Sundays.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The team was replaced by the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] 1881 would be the final season of the first National League monopoly-era, as the American Association would be established in 1882.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The 1881 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since 1879 and would be used until 1883.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring four teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring all eight teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Two tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues, Providence Grays, Troy Trojans, and Worcester Worcesters had one tie game each.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines join the National League and play at Recreation Park in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans would play their final game at Haymakers' Grounds on September 30 against the Detroit Wolverines, moving to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds for the start of the 1882 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing on June 15 and September 10.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Formed in 1876 and 1901, respectively, the NL and AL cemented their cooperation with the National Agreement in 1903, making MLB the oldest major professional sports league in the United States and Canada.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] They remained legally separate entities until 2000, when they merged into a single organization led by the commissioner of baseball.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball's first all-professional team, the Cincinnati Red Stockings, was founded in 1869.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The first few decades of professional baseball saw rivalries between leagues, and players often jumped from one team or league to another.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] These practices were essentially ended by the National Agreement of 1903, in which AL and NL agreed to respect each other's player contracts, including the contentious reserve clause, which bound players to their teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The period from about 1900 to 1920 was the dead-ball era, when home runs were rarely hit.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Professional baseball was rocked by the Black Sox Scandal, a conspiracy to fix the 1919 World Series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball survived the scandal, albeit with major changes in its governance, as the relatively weak National Commission was replaced with a powerful commissioner of baseball with near-unlimited authority over the sport.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB rose in popularity in the decade following the Black Sox Scandal, and unlike major leagues in other sports, it endured the Great Depression and World War II without any of its teams folding.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Shortly after the war, Jackie Robinson broke baseball's color barrier.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Some teams moved to different cities in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The AL and NL added eight clubs in the 1960s, which started the expansion era: two in 1961, two in 1962, and four in 1969.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Player discontent with established labor practices, especially the reserve clause, led to the organization of the Major League Baseball Players Association to collectively bargain with the owners, which in turn led to the introduction of free agency in baseball.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Modern stadiums with artificial turf surfaces began to change the game in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Home runs began to dominate the game during the 1990s.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In the mid-2000s, media reports disclosed the use of anabolic steroids among MLB players; a 2006–07 investigation produced the *Mitchell Report*, which found that many players had used steroids and other performance-enhancing substances, including at least one player from each team.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB is the third-wealthiest professional sports league in the world by revenue after the National Football League (NFL) and the National Basketball Association (NBA).
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball games are broadcast on television, radio, and the internet throughout North America and in several other countries.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB has the highest total season attendance of any sports league in the world; in 2025, it drew 71.4 million spectators.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB also oversees Minor League Baseball, which comprises lower-tier teams affiliated with the major league clubs, the MLB Draft League, a hybrid amateur-professional showcase league, and the Arizona Fall League, an off-season showcase league for minor league players.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB and the World Baseball Softball Confederation jointly manage the international World Baseball Classic tournament.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The New York Yankees have the most championships with 27.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The reigning champions are the Los Angeles Dodgers, who defeated the Toronto Blue Jays in the 2025 World Series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In the 1860s, aided by soldiers playing the game in camp during the Civil War, "New York"-style baseball expanded into a national game and spawned baseball's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP).
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The NABBP existed as an amateur league for 12 years.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] By 1867, more than 400 clubs were members.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Most of the strongest clubs remained those based in the northeastern United States.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] For professional baseball's founding year, MLB uses the year 1869—when the first professional team, the Cincinnati Red Stockings, was established.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] A schism developed between professional and amateur ballplayers after the founding of the Cincinnati club.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The NABBP split into an amateur organization and a professional organization.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The National Association of Professional Base Ball Players, often known as the National Association (NA), was formed in 1871.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Its amateur counterpart disappeared after only a few years.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The modern Chicago Cubs and Atlanta Braves franchises trace their histories back to the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players in the 1870s.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1876, the National League of Professional Base Ball Clubs (later known as the National League or NL) was established after the NA proved ineffective.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The league placed its emphasis on clubs rather than on players.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Clubs could now enforce player contracts, preventing players from jumping to higher-paying clubs.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Clubs were required to play the full schedule of games instead of forfeiting scheduled games when the club was no longer in the running for the league championship, which happened frequently under the NA.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] A concerted effort was made to curb gambling on games, which was leaving the validity of results in doubt.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The first game in the NL—on Saturday, April 22, 1876 (at Jefferson Street Grounds in Philadelphia)—is often pointed to as the beginning of MLB.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The early years of the NL were tumultuous, with threats from rival leagues and a rebellion by players against the hated "reserve clause", which restricted the free movement of players between clubs.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Teams came and went; 1882 was the first season where the league's membership was the same as the preceding season's, and only four franchises survived to see 1900.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Competitor leagues formed regularly and also disbanded regularly.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The most successful was the American Association (1882–1891), sometimes called the "beer and whiskey league" for its tolerance of the sale of alcoholic beverages to spectators.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] For several years, the NL and American Association champions met in a postseason championship series—the first attempt at a World Series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The two leagues merged in 1892 as a single 12-team NL, but the NL dropped four teams after the 1899 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] This led to the formation of the American League (AL) in 1901 under president Ban Johnson, and the resulting bidding war for players led to widespread contract-breaking and legal disputes.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The war between the AL and NL sent shockwaves throughout the baseball world.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] At a meeting at the Leland Hotel in Chicago in 1901, the other baseball leagues negotiated a plan to maintain their independence.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] A new National Association was formed to oversee these minor leagues.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] After 1902, the NL, AL, and NA signed a new National Agreement, which tied independent contracts to the reserve-clause contracts.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The agreement also set up a formal classification system for minor leagues, the forerunner of today's system that was refined by Branch Rickey.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Several other early defunct baseball leagues are considered major leagues, and their statistics and records are included with those of the two modern major leagues.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1969, the Special Baseball Records Committee of Major League Baseball officially recognized six major leagues: the National League, American League, American Association, Union Association (1884), Players' League (1890), and Federal League (1914–1915).
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The status of the National Association as a major league has been a point of dispute among baseball researchers; while its statistics are not recognized by Major League Baseball, its statistics *are* included with those of other major leagues by some baseball reference websites, such as Retrosheet.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Some researchers, including Nate Silver, dispute the major-league status of the Union Association by pointing out that franchises came and went and that the St.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis club was deliberately "stacked"; the St.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis club was owned by the league's president and it was the only club that was close to major-league caliber.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2021, baseball reference website Baseball-Reference.com began to include statistics from those seven leagues into their major-league statistics.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The period between 1900 and 1919 is commonly referred to as the "dead-ball era".
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Games of this era tended to be low-scoring and were often dominated by pitchers, such as Walter Johnson, Cy Young, Christy Mathewson, Mordecai Brown, and Grover Cleveland Alexander.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The term also accurately describes the condition of the baseball itself.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The baseball used American rather than the modern Australian wool yarn and was not wound as tightly, affecting the distance that it would travel.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] More significantly, balls were kept in play until they were mangled, soft and sometimes lopsided.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] During this era, a baseball cost $3, (equivalent to $56 in 2025), and owners were reluctant to purchase new balls.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Fans were expected to throw back fouls and (rare) home runs.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseballs also became stained with tobacco juice, grass, and mud, and sometimes the juice of licorice, which some players would chew for the purpose of discoloring the ball.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Also, pitchers could manipulate the ball through the use of the spitball (In 1921, use of this pitch was restricted to a few pitchers with a grandfather clause).
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Hitting methods like the Baltimore chop were used to increase the number of infield singles.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] On a successful Baltimore chop, the batter hits the ball forcefully into the ground, causing it to bounce so high that the batter reaches first base before the ball can be fielded and thrown to the first baseman.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The adoption of the foul strike rule—in the NL in 1901, in the AL two years later—quickly sent baseball from a high-scoring game to one where scoring runs became a struggle.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Before this rule, foul balls were not counted as strikes: a batter could foul off any number of pitches with no strikes counted against him; this gave an enormous advantage to the batter.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] After the 1919 World Series between the Chicago White Sox and Cincinnati Reds, baseball was rocked by allegations of a game-fixing scheme known as the Black Sox Scandal.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Eight players—"Shoeless" Joe Jackson, Eddie Cicotte, Claude "Lefty" Williams, George "Buck" Weaver, Arnold "Chick" Gandil, Fred McMullin, Charles "Swede" Risberg, and Oscar "Happy" Felsch—intentionally lost the World Series in exchange for a ring worth $100,000 (equivalent to $1,860,000 in 2025).
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Despite being acquitted, all were permanently banned from MLB.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball's popularity increased in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The 1920 season was notable for the death of Ray Chapman of the Cleveland Indians.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Chapman, who was struck in the head by a pitch and died a few hours later, became the only MLB player to die of an on-field injury.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Both leagues quickly began to require the use of new, white baseballs whenever a ball became scuffed or dirty, helping bring the "dead-ball" era to an end.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The following year, the New York Yankees made their first World Series appearance.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] By the end of the 1930s, the team had appeared in 11 World Series, winning eight of them.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Yankees slugger Babe Ruth had set the single-season home run record in 1927, hitting 60 home runs; breaking his own record of 29 home runs.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Impacted negatively by the Great Depression, baseball's popularity had begun a downward turn in the early 1930s.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] By 1932, only two MLB teams turned a profit.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Attendance had fallen, due at least in part to a 10% federal amusement tax added to baseball ticket prices.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball owners cut their rosters from 25 men to 23, and even the best players took pay cuts.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Team executives were innovative in their attempts to survive, creating night games, broadcasting games live by radio, and rolling out promotions such as free admission for women.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Throughout the Great Depression, no MLB teams moved or folded.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The onset of World War II created a shortage of professional baseball players, as more than 500 men left MLB teams to serve in the military.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Many of them played on service baseball teams that entertained military personnel in the US or in the Pacific.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB teams of this time largely consisted of young men, older players, and those with a military classification of 4F, indicating mental, physical, or moral unsuitability for service.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Men like Pete Gray, a one-armed outfielder, got the chance to advance to the major leagues.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] However, MLB rosters did not include any black players through the end of the war.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Black players, many of whom served in the war, were still restricted to playing Negro league baseball.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Wartime blackout restrictions, designed to keep outdoor lighting at low levels, caused another problem for baseball.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] These rules limited traveling and night games to the point that the 1942 season was nearly canceled.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] On January 14, 1942, MLB commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis wrote to U.S. president Franklin D.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Roosevelt, pleading for the continuation of baseball during the war.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Roosevelt responded, "I honestly feel that it would be best for the country to keep baseball going.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] There will be fewer people unemployed and everybody will work longer hours and harder than ever before.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] With President Roosevelt's approval, spring training began in 1942 with few repercussions.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The war interrupted the careers of stars including Stan Musial, Bob Feller, Ted Williams, and Joe DiMaggio, but baseball clubs continued to field their teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Branch Rickey, president and general manager of the Brooklyn Dodgers, began making efforts to introduce a black baseball player to the previously all-white professional baseball leagues in the mid-1940s.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] He selected Jackie Robinson from a list of promising Negro league players.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] After obtaining a commitment from Robinson to "turn the other cheek" to any racial antagonism directed at him, Rickey agreed to sign him to a contract for $600 a month (equivalent to $9,906 in 2025).
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In what was later referred to as "The Noble Experiment", Robinson was the first black baseball player in the International League since the 1880s, joining the Dodgers' farm club, the Montreal Royals, for the 1946 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The following year, the Dodgers called up Robinson to the major leagues.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] On April 15, 1947, Robinson made his major league debut at Ebbets Field before a crowd of 26,623 spectators, including more than 14,000 black patrons.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Black baseball fans began flocking to see the Dodgers when they came to town, abandoning the Negro league teams that they had followed exclusively.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Robinson's promotion met a generally positive, although mixed, reception among newspaper writers and white major league players.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Manager Leo Durocher informed his team, "I don't care if he is yellow or black or has stripes like a fucking zebra.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] After a strike threat by some players, NL president Ford C.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Frick and Commissioner Happy Chandler let it be known that any striking players would be suspended.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Robinson received significant encouragement from several major-league players, including Dodgers teammate Pee Wee Reese who said, "You can hate a man for many reasons.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Color is not one of them." That year, Robinson won the inaugural Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award (separate NL and AL Rookie of the Year honors were not awarded until 1949).
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Less than three months later, Larry Doby became the first African-American to break the color barrier in the American League with the Cleveland Indians.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The next year, a number of other black players entered the major leagues.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Satchel Paige was signed by the Indians and the Dodgers added star catcher Roy Campanella and Don Newcombe, who was later the first winner of the Cy Young Award for his outstanding pitching.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB banned the signing of women to contracts in 1952, but that ban was lifted in 1992.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] There have been no female MLB players since then.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] From 1903 to 1952, the major leagues consisted of two eight-team leagues whose 16 teams were located in ten cities, all in the northeastern and mid-western United States: New York City had three teams and Boston, Chicago, Philadelphia, and St.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis was the southernmost and westernmost city with a major league team.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The longest possible road trip, from Boston to St.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] After a half-century of stability, starting in the 1950s, teams began to move out of cities with multiple teams into cities that had not had them before.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] From 1953 to 1955, three teams moved to new cities: the Boston Braves became the Milwaukee Braves, the St.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis Browns became the Baltimore Orioles, and the Philadelphia Athletics became the Kansas City Athletics.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The 1958 season began to turn Major League Baseball into a nationwide league.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Walter O'Malley, owner of the Brooklyn Dodgers and "perhaps the most influential owner of baseball's early expansion era", moved his team to Los Angeles, marking the first major league franchise on the West Coast.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] O'Malley also helped persuade the rival New York Giants to move west to become the San Francisco Giants.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Giants owner Horace Stoneham had been contemplating a move to Minnesota amid slumping attendance at the aging Polo Grounds ballpark when O'Malley invited him to meet San Francisco mayor George Christopher in New York.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] After Stoneham was persuaded to move to California, *Time* magazine put O'Malley on its cover.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Frick had opposed the meeting, but the dual moves proved successful for both franchises and for MLB.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Had the Dodgers moved out west alone, the St.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals—1,600 mi (2,575 km) away—would have been the closest NL team.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Instead, the joint move made West Coast road trips economical for visiting teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The Dodgers set a single-game MLB attendance record in their first home appearance with 78,672 fans.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1961, the first Washington Senators franchise moved to Minneapolis–Saint Paul to become the Minnesota Twins.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Two new teams were added to the American League at the same time: the Los Angeles Angels (who soon moved from downtown L.A. to nearby Anaheim) and a new Washington Senators franchise.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The NL added the Houston Astros and the New York Mets in 1962.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The Astros (known as the "Colt .45s" during their first three seasons) became the first southern major league franchise since the Louisville Colonels folded in 1899 and the first franchise to be located along the Gulf Coast.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1966, the major leagues moved to the "Deep South" when the Milwaukee Braves moved to Atlanta.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1968, the Kansas City Athletics moved west to become the Oakland Athletics.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1969, the American and National Leagues both added two expansion franchises.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The American League added the Seattle Pilots (who became the Milwaukee Brewers after one disastrous season in Seattle) and the Kansas City Royals.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The NL added the first Canadian franchise, the Montreal Expos, as well as the San Diego Padres.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1972, the second Washington Senators moved to the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex to become the Texas Rangers.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1977, baseball expanded again, adding a second Canadian team, the Toronto Blue Jays, as well as the Seattle Mariners.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Subsequently, no new teams were added until 1993, and no teams moved until 2005.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] By the late 1960s, the balance between pitching and hitting had swung in favor of the pitchers.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1968—later nicknamed "the year of the pitcher"—Boston Red Sox player Carl Yastrzemski won the American League batting title with an average of just .301, the lowest in MLB history.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Detroit Tigers pitcher Denny McLain won 31 games, making him the only pitcher to win 30 games in a season since Dizzy Dean in 1934.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals starting pitcher Bob Gibson achieved an equally remarkable feat by allowing an ERA of just 1.12.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Following these pitching performances, in December 1968 the MLB Playing Rules Committee voted to reduce the strike zone from knees to shoulders to top of knees to armpits and lower the pitcher's mound from 15 to 10 inches, beginning in the 1969 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1973, the American League, which had been suffering from much lower attendance than the National League, sought to increase scoring even further by initiating the designated hitter (DH) rule.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Throughout the 1960s and 1970s, as baseball expanded, the National Football League (NFL) had been surging in popularity, making it economical for many of these cities to build multi-purpose stadiums instead of single-purpose baseball fields.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Because of climate and economic issues, many of these facilities had playing surfaces made from artificial turf, as well as the oval designs characteristic of stadiums designed to house both baseball and football.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] This often resulted in baseball fields with relatively more foul territory than older stadiums.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] These characteristics changed the nature of professional baseball, putting a higher premium on speed and defense over home-run hitting power since the fields were often too big for teams to expect to hit many home runs and foul balls hit in the air could more easily be caught for outs.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Teams began to be built around pitching—particularly their bullpens—and speed on the basepaths.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Artificial surfaces meant balls traveled quicker and bounced higher, so it became easier to hit ground balls "in the hole" between the corner and middle infielders.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Starting pitchers were no longer expected to throw complete games; it was enough for a starter to pitch 6–7 innings and turn the game over to the team's closer, a position which grew in importance over these decades.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] As stolen bases increased, home run totals dropped.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] After Willie Mays hit 52 home runs in 1965, only one player (George Foster) reached that mark until the 1990s.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] During the 1980s, baseball experienced a number of significant changes the game had not seen in years.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Home runs were on the decline throughout the decade, with players hitting 40 home runs just 13 times and no one hitting more than 50 home runs in a season for the first time since the dead-ball era (1900–1919).
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The 1981 MLB strike from June 12 until July 31 forced the cancellation of 713 games and resulted in a split-season format.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1985, Pete Rose broke Ty Cobb's all-time hits record with his 4,192nd hit.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1989, Rose received a lifetime ban from baseball as a result of betting on baseball games while manager of the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Rose was the first person to receive a lifetime ban from baseball since 1943.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] 1985 also saw the Pittsburgh drug trials which involved players who were called to testify before a grand jury in Pittsburgh related to cocaine trafficking.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The 1994–95 MLB strike from August 12, 1994, to April 25, 1995, caused the cancellation of over 900 games and the forfeit of the entire 1994 postseason.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Routinely in the late 1990s and early 2000s, baseball players hit 40 or 50 home runs in a season, a feat that was considered rare even in the 1980s.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] It later became apparent that at least some of this power surge was a result of players using steroids and other performance-enhancing drugs.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1993, the National League added the Florida Marlins in Miami and the Colorado Rockies in Denver.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1998, the Brewers switched leagues by joining the National League, and two new teams were added: the National League's Arizona Diamondbacks in Phoenix and the American League's Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] After the 2001 season, the team owners voted in favor of contraction.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Several MLB teams had been considered for elimination in early talks about contraction, but the Montreal Expos and the Minnesota Twins were the two teams that came closest to folding under the plan.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Plans for MLB contraction were halted when the Twins landlord was awarded a court injunction that required the team to play its 2002 home games at their stadium.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB owners agreed to hold off on reducing the league's size until at least 2006.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The Montreal Expos became the first franchise in over three decades to move when they became the Washington Nationals in 2005.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] This move left Canada with just one team, but it also returned baseball to Washington after a 33-year absence.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] This franchise shift, like many previous ones, involved baseball's return to a city that had been previously abandoned.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In recent years, with the advent of technologies such as Statcast and its use of Hawk-Eye starting in 2020 as well as with advanced statistics as provided by sites such as FanGraphs and Baseball Savant, MLB has evolved.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] With the ability to see precise movements of pitchers and batters, teams can assess the mechanics of a player and help them improve.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Statcast also provides some features such as tracking the paths of most batted balls, tracking the speed of most batted balls, and tracking the exit velocity of most batted balls.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Statcast has allowed for advanced defensive analytics that have not been possible before tracking of players due to how subjective fielding can be.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The rate of teams using a defensive shift went up from 13.7% in 2016 to 33.6% in 2022 because advanced statistics supported this as an effective way to stop hitters from getting hits.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Because the shift reduces the number of balls in play that result in hits and MLB wishes to increase interest in baseball, MLB announced in September 2022 that extreme infield defensive shifts would be banned starting in 2023.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] To be compliant, there must be two fielders on each side of second base, and those fielders must have both of their feet on the infield dirt at the time the pitch is thrown.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] If this rule is not followed, the choice of an automatic ball or the outcome of the play is given to the batting team.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The game of baseball has also slowed down significantly due to an increased number of strikeouts and walks—two outcomes that generally take many pitches to complete—and an increased amount of time taken for a pitcher to pitch.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2020, it took an average of three hours and six minutes to complete a 9 inning game, a number which has steadily ticked up for years.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Along with the restrictions on defensive shifts, MLB announced the introduction of a pitch clock for the 2023 season and beyond, which is something that has been an experiment in MiLB for a few years.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] By the time the clock reaches 10 seconds, the catcher must be in their crouch behind home plate.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] When the clock reaches 8 seconds, the batter must be in the batter's box and be "alert".
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Before the 15 second timer reaches 0 seconds, the pitcher must have started their "motion to pitch".
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] If any of these deadlines are violated, the count of the batter will be increased by one ball if the defending team violated the pitch clock or one strike if it is the offensive team who violated the pitch clock.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Additionally, in order to prevent circumventing these rules, pickoffs and step-offs — which reset the pitch clock — are only allowed two times total per plate appearance, and if a pitcher attempts a third pickoff and fails to get the runner out, a ball will be called.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Similarly, a batter is restricted to calling a timeout (an action which resets the pitch clock) just once per plate appearance.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2019, MLB opened an investigation into allegations that members of the 2017 World Series champion Houston Astros stole signs from opposing teams using technology during the 2017 and 2018 seasons.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The Astros were found guilty in January 2020 and while no active players faced any repercussions due to an immunity agreement in exchange for testimony, Astros general manager Jeff Luhnow and field manager A.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Hinch were suspended for the entire 2020 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The Astros were fined the maximum allowable $5 million and forfeited their first- and second-round picks in the 2020 and 2021 drafts.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The Boston Red Sox were also found guilty of stealing signs during the 2017 and 2018 seasons, with the latter season ending in a World Series victory.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Red Sox manager Alex Cora was suspended for a year and the team was fined with the loss of a second-round draft pick in the 2020 draft as a result.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In November 2023, the Oakland Athletics relocation to Las Vegas was approved by MLB owners.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] They are to play the 2025 through 2027 seasons in West Sacramento, California, while a new stadium is built in the Las Vegas metropolitan area, and will be referred to as simply the "Athletics" and "A's", with no city name attached.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB has discussed preparations for another round of expansion, and several investment groups are vying for a franchise.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2025, commissioner Rob Manfred said MLB could add two teams and pursue a geographic realignment of its leagues and divisions.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB is governed by the Major League Baseball Constitution.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] This document has undergone several incarnations since its creation in 1876.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Under the direction of the commissioner of baseball, MLB hires and maintains the sport's umpiring crews, and negotiates marketing, labor, and television contracts.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB maintains a unique, controlling relationship over the sport, including most aspects of Minor League Baseball.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] This is due in large part to the 1922 U.S.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Supreme Court ruling in *Federal Baseball Club v.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] National League*, which held that baseball is not interstate commerce and therefore not subject to federal antitrust law; MLB is the only league that has such a status, and has not faced any competition since this case.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] This ruling has been weakened only slightly in subsequent years.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The weakened ruling granted more stability to the owners of teams and has resulted in values increasing at double-digit rates.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] There were several challenges to MLB's primacy in the sport, with notable attempts to establish competing leagues occurring during the late 1800s, from 1913 to 1915 with the short-lived Federal League, and in 1960 with the aborted Continental League.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The chief executive of MLB is the commissioner, Rob Manfred.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The deputy commissioner of baseball administration and chief legal officer is Dan Halem.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The multimedia branch of MLB is MLB Advanced Media, which is based in New York City.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] This branch oversees MLB.com and each of the 30 teams' websites.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Its charter states that MLB Advanced Media holds editorial independence from the league, but it is under the same ownership group and revenue-sharing plan.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB Productions is a similarly structured wing of the league, focusing on video and traditional broadcast media.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB also owns 67 percent of MLB Network, with the other 33 percent split between several cable operators and satellite provider DirecTV.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] It operates out of studios in Secaucus, New Jersey, and also has editorial independence from the league.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1920, the weak National Commission, created to manage relationships between the two leagues, was replaced with the much more powerful commissioner of baseball, who had the power to make decisions for all of professional baseball unilaterally.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] From 1901 to 1960, the American League and National League fielded eight teams apiece.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In the 1960s, MLB expansion added eight teams, including the first non-U.S. team (the Montreal Expos).
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Two teams (the Seattle Mariners and the Toronto Blue Jays) were also added in the 1970s.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] From 1969 through 1993, each league consisted of an East and West Division.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1993, the National League expanded with two teams, the Florida Marlins and the Colorado Rockies, to even up the number of teams in both leagues.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] A third division, the Central Division, was formed in each league in 1994.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Until 1996, the two leagues met on the field only during the World Series and the All-Star Game.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In March 1995, two new franchises, the Arizona Diamondbacks and Tampa Bay Devil Rays (now known as the Tampa Bay Rays), were awarded by MLB, which began play in 1998.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] This addition brought the total number of franchises to 30.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In early 1997, MLB decided to assign one new team to each league: Tampa Bay joined the AL and Arizona joined the NL.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The original plan was to have an odd number of teams in each league (15 per league, with five in each division), but in order for every team to be able to play daily, this would have required interleague play to be scheduled throughout the entire season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] However, it was unclear at the time if the interleague play would continue after the 1998 season, as it had to be approved by the players' union.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] For this and other reasons, it was decided that both leagues should continue to have an even number of teams, and therefore, one existing club would have to switch leagues.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed in November 1997 to move from the AL to the NL, thereby making the AL a 14-team league and the NL a 16-team league.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers agreed to move from the AL East to the AL Central (to replace Milwaukee), with the expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays joining the AL East.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Later, when the Houston Astros changed ownership prior to the 2013 season, the team moved from the NL Central to the AL West, resulting in both leagues having three divisions of five teams each and allowing all teams to have a more balanced schedule.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Interleague play is now held throughout the season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2000, the AL and NL were dissolved as legal entities, and MLB became a single, overall league *de jure*, similar to the National Football League (NFL), National Basketball Association (NBA) and National Hockey League (NHL)—albeit with two components called "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The use of "major-league baseball" to refer to the overall AL–NL construct prior to 2000 is preferred, since statements such as "In 1942, Ted Williams led MLB with 36 homers, 137 RBIs, a .356 batting average, and won the first of his two Triple Crowns" are anachronistic.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Since becoming a single entity, common rules and regulations have been used in both MLB leagues, with one former exception: the AL continued operating under the designated hitter (DH) rule, while the NL did not.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2020, the NL used the DH rule for the first time.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] As part of the settlement of the 2021–22 Major League Baseball lockout, this change was made permanent, thus making the rules in the two leagues identical.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] A baseball uniform is a type of uniform worn by baseball players and by some non-playing personnel, such as field managers and coaches.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] It is worn to indicate the person's role in the game and—through the use of logos, colors, and numbers—to identify the teams and their players, managers, and coaches.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Traditionally, home uniforms display the team name on the front, while away uniforms display the team's home location.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In modern times, however, exceptions to this pattern have become common, with teams using their team name on both uniforms.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Most teams also have one or more alternate uniforms, usually consisting of the primary or secondary team color on the vest instead of the usual white or gray.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In the past few decades throwback uniforms have become popular.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] The New York Knickerbockers were the first baseball team to use uniforms, taking the field on April 4, 1849, in pants made of blue wool, white flannel shirts (jerseys) and straw hats.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Caps and other types of headgear have been a part of baseball uniforms from the beginning.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball teams often wore full-brimmed straw hats or no cap at all since there was no official rule regarding headgear.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] Under the 1882 uniform rules, players on the same team wore uniforms of different colors and patterns that indicated which position they played.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] This rule was soon abandoned as impractical.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In the late 1880s, Detroit and Washington of the National League and Brooklyn of the American Association were the first to wear striped uniforms.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] By the end of the 19th century, teams began the practice of having two different uniforms, one for when they played at home in their own baseball stadium and a different one for when they played away (on the road) at the other team's ballpark.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] It became common to wear white pants with a white color vest at home and gray pants with a gray or solid (dark) colored vest when away.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] By 1900, both home and away uniforms were standard across the major leagues.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] In June 2021, MLB announced a long-term deal with cryptocurrency exchange FTX, which includes the FTX logo appearing on umpire uniforms during all games.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] FTX is MLB's first-ever umpire uniform patch partner.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] On November 11, 2022, FTX filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB removed the FTX patches from umpires' uniforms before the 2023 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Spring training is a series of practices and exhibition games preceding the start of the regular season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Teams hold training camps in the states of Arizona and Florida, where the early warm weather allows teams to practice and play without worrying about the late winter cold.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Spring training allows new players to compete for roster and position spots and gives existing team players practice time prior to competitive play.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The teams that hold spring training in Arizona are grouped into the Cactus League, while teams that hold camp in Florida are known as the Grapefruit League.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Spring training typically lasts almost two months, starting in mid-February and running until just before the season-opening day, traditionally the first week of April.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] As pitchers benefit from a longer training period, pitchers and catchers begin spring training several days before the rest of the team.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] A team's schedule is typically organized into three-game series, sets of consecutive games against the same opponent, with occasional two- or four-game series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Postponed games or continuations of suspended games can result in an ad hoc one-game or five-game series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] All games of a series are usually hosted by the same team, and multiple series are typically grouped together.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] I.e, a team usually hosts several series in a row, called a homestand, and follows that by going on several road series in a row.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Teams generally play games five to seven days per week.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Most games are scheduled at night, although teams will often play day games on Opening Day, holidays, and for the last game of a series to allow teams extra time to travel to their next opponent.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Sunday games are generally played during the afternoon, allowing teams to travel to their next destination prior to a Monday night game.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In the current three-division structure, each team plays 13 games against each of its four divisional opponents.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] It plays one home series and one away series, amounting to six or seven games, against the 10 other teams in its league.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] A team also plays 3-game series with all the other teams in the other league, alternating home teams each year.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Furthermore, each team has an interleague "natural rival" (in some cases its counterpart in the same metro area) with which it plays three home games and three away games each year.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] With an odd number of teams in each league (15), it is necessary to have two teams participate in interleague play for most days in the season, except when two or more teams have a day off.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] From 2013 to 2022, each team played 20 interleague games throughout the season, usually with just one interleague game per day, but for one weekend in late May, all teams would participate in an interleague series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] (Season-long interleague play was not necessary before 2013 as each league had an even number of teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2013, the Houston Astros moved to the American League, so that each league would have 15 teams.) Prior to the adoption of the universal designated hitter in 2022, whether the DH was in use depended on whether the home team was from the AL, where the DH was used, or the NL, where it was not.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting with the 2023 season, the scheduling formula changed, with each team playing at least one series against every other team every year.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Beginning with the 2022 season, teams compete for the six playoff berths in their respective leagues.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] To secure a berth, a team must either win its division or capture a wild card spot by having one of the three best records among the non-winners in its entire league.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] With the adoption of a third wild card, the former practice of breaking ties with an additional regular-season game, known as Game 163, was dropped in favor of a tie-breaker formula.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In early-to-mid July, just after the midway point of the season, the Major League Baseball All-Star Game is held during a four-day break from the regular-season schedule.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The All-Star Game features a team of players from the American League (AL)—led by the manager of the previous AL World Series team—and a team of players from the National League (NL), similarly managed, in an exhibition game.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] From 1959 to 1962, two games were held each season, one was held in July and one was held in August.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The designated-hitter rule was used in the All-Star Game for the first time in 1989.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Following games used a DH when the game was played in an AL ballpark.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2010, the DH rule has been in effect regardless of venue.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The first official All-Star Game was held as part of the 1933 World's Fair in Chicago, Illinois, and was the idea of Arch Ward, then sports editor for *The Chicago Tribune*.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Initially intended to be a one-time event, its great success resulted in making the game an annual one.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Ward's contribution was recognized by Major League Baseball in 1962 with the creation of the "Arch Ward Trophy", given to the All-Star Game's Most Valuable Player each year.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] (In 1970, it was renamed the Commissioner's Trophy, until 1985, when the name change was reversed.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Beginning in 1947, the eight position players in each team's starting lineup have been voted into the game by fans.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The fan voting was discontinued after a 1957 ballot-box-stuffing scandal in Cincinnati: seven of the eight slots originally went to Reds players, two of whom were subsequently removed from the lineup to make room for Willie Mays and Hank Aaron.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Fan voting was reinstated in 1970 and has continued ever since, including internet voting in recent years.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The 2002 contest in Milwaukee controversially ended in an 11-inning tie when both managers ran out of pitchers.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In response, starting in 2003 the league which wins the All-Star game received home-field advantage in the World Series: the league champion hosted the first two games at its own ballpark as well as the last two (if necessary).
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The National League did not win an All-Star game and thus gain a home-field advantage until 2010; it was able to overcome this disadvantage and win in three of the seven World Series from 2003 to 2009.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] This was discontinued after the 2016 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] MLB All-Stars from both leagues have worn uniforms from their respective teams at the game with one exception.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In the 1933 All-Star Game, the National League All-Star Team members wore special gray uniforms with "National League" written in navy blue letters across the front of the jersey.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The regular season ends after the first Sunday in October (or the last Sunday in September), after which twelve teams enter the postseason playoffs.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] These twelve teams consist of the six division champions and six "wild-card" teams: the team with the best overall win–loss record in each of the six divisions, and the three teams in each league with the best records other than the division champions.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] American League Division Series and National League Division Series, each a best-of-five-games series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] American League Championship Series and National League Championship Series, each a best-of-seven-games series played between the winning teams from the Division Series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The league champions are referred to as the pennant winners.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] World Series, a best-of-seven-games series played between the pennant winners of each league.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Within each league, the division winners are the 1, 2, and 3-seeds, based on win–loss records.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The teams with the first, second, and third best records among non-division winners will be seeded 4, 5, and 6 respectively.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Throughout the postseason, home-field advantage is awarded to the team with the higher win-loss record, with tiebreakers being applied if necessary.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In the Wild Card Series, the 3-seed will host the 6-seed, and the 4-seed will host the 5-seed, with the winners advancing to the Division Series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Unlike the NFL, there is no reseeding between each series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In the Division Series, the 1-seed goes up against the 4/5-seed and the 2-seed goes up against the 3/6-seed.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The winners of those matches will compete in their respective League Championship Series for their league pennant, and the pennant winners will advance to the World Series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2017, home-field advantage in the World Series is determined by regular-season records of the two league champions, replacing a system used for the prior 14 seasons where the champion of the league that won the All-Star Game would receive home-field advantage.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] With this format, the home-field advantage does not usually play a large role in the postseason unless the series goes to its maximum number of games.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] However, because the first two games of a postseason series are hosted by the same team, a team starting with two wins will likely have momentum heading into the venue switch.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] From 1986 to 2018, an MLB All-Star team was sent to a biennial end-of-the-season tour of Japan, dubbed the MLB Japan All-Star Series, playing exhibition games in a best-of format against the All-Stars from Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB) or, in 2014 and 2018, their national team, Samurai Japan.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB played the MLB China Series in the People's Republic of China.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] It was a series of two spring-training games between the San Diego Padres and Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The games were an effort to popularize baseball in China.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] MLB played the MLB Taiwan All-Star Series in Taiwan in November 2011.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] It was a series of five exhibition games played by a team made up of MLB players called the MLB All-Stars and the Chinese Taipei national baseball team.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The MLB All-Stars swept the series, five games to zero.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] At the end of the 2011 season, it was announced that the Seattle Mariners and the Oakland Athletics would play their season openers in Japan.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In October 2013, Phil Rogers of the *Chicago Tribune* wrote that MLB was considering postseason all-star tours in Taiwan and Korea; baseball is increasing in popularity in both countries.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The Arizona Diamondbacks opened the 2014 season against Los Angeles Dodgers from March 22–23 in Australia.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The teams played each other at the historic Sydney Cricket Ground, which has a seating capacity of 46,000.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The two games represented the first MLB regular-season play held in that country.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The games counted as home games for the Diamondbacks, so they played 79 home games at Chase Field.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2019, the Boston Red Sox were the home team in a regular-season two-game series against the New York Yankees.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The games, which were the first regular-season MLB games held in Europe, were played on June 29–30 at London Stadium with the Yankees winning both games.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The San Diego Padres and Los Angeles Dodgers opened the 2024 regular season on March 20–21 at Gocheok Sky Dome in Seoul, South Korea.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The ceremonial first pitch of the opening game was thrown by the first Korean-born MLB player Chan Ho Park, who made his debut with the LA Dodgers in 1994.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The two-game Seoul Series resulted in a split between the two teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] There were also four exhibition games played during March 17–18, where the Dodgers took on the Kiwoom Heroes and Team Korea, and the Padres faced the LG Twins and Team Korea.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The 2025 season began with the Los Angeles Dodgers and the Chicago Cubs playing in Tokyo at the Tokyo Dome for the MLB Tokyo Series 2025.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Together with the World Baseball Softball Confederation, MLB sponsors the World Baseball Classic, an international baseball tournament contested by national teams.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In 1998, both Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa hit more home runs than the record of 61 set by Yankees right fielder Roger Maris in 1961.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Barry Bonds topped the record in 2001 with 73 home runs.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] McGwire, Bonds, and Sosa became the subjects of speculation regarding the use of performance-enhancing substances.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] McGwire later admitted that he used a steroid hormone that was still legal in baseball during the 1998 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Baseball's original steroid testing policy, in effect from 2002 to 2005, provided for penalties ranging from a ten-game suspension for a first positive test to a one-year suspension for a fourth positive test.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Players were tested at least once per year, with the chance that several players could be tested many times per year.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell was appointed by Selig on March 30, 2006 to investigate the use of performance-enhancing drugs in MLB.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The appointment was made after several influential members of the U.S.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Congress made negative comments about both the effectiveness and honesty of MLB's drug policies and Commissioner Selig.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] It pointed out that HGH is likely a placebo with no performance-enhancing effects.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The report included substance use allegations against at least one player from each MLB team.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] According to ESPN, some people questioned whether Mitchell's director role with the Boston Red Sox created a conflict of interest, especially because no "prime [Sox] players were in the report".
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The report named several prominent Yankees who were parts of World Series clubs; there is a long-running and fierce Yankees–Red Sox rivalry.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Dowd brought up Mitchell's conflict of interest, but he later said that the former senator had done a good job.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Mitchell acknowledged that his "tight relationship with Major League Baseball left him open to criticism", but he said that readers who examine the report closely "will not find any evidence of bias, of special treatment of the Red Sox".
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] On January 10, 2013, MLB and the players union reached an agreement to add random, in-season HGH testing.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] They also agreed to implement a new test to reveal the use of testosterone for the 2013 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The current MLB drug policy provides for an 80-game suspension for a first positive test, a 162-game suspension for a second positive test, and a lifetime suspension for a third positive test.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2009, allegations surfaced against Alex Rodriguez and David Ortiz, and Manny Ramirez received a 50-game suspension after testing positive for banned substances.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In early April 2011, Ramirez retired from baseball rather than face a 100-game suspension for his second positive steroid test.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] He would later unretire, having the suspension dropped to 50 games, and would serve those in 2012.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting in 2026, Fox, ESPN, NBC, TBS, and MLB Network will nationally televise MLB games in the United States.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Fox has been MLB's primary broadcast television partner since 1996.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2008, Fox has broadcast MLB games on Saturdays throughout the entire season; Fox previously only broadcast games from May to September.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Fox also holds rights to the All-Star Game each season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Fox also alternates League Championship Series broadcasts, broadcasting the American League Championship Series (ALCS) in odd-numbered years and the National League Championship Series (NLCS) in even-numbered years.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Fox broadcasts all games of the World Series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] ESPN has been MLB's cable television partner since 1990.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The network has aired the weekly regular season game *Sunday Night Baseball* and postseason broadcasts of the Wild Card Series exclusively.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] TBS began airing Sunday afternoon regular season games (non-exclusive) nationally in 2008, which was then replaced by Tuesday night games in 2022.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] From 2007 to 2020, TBS had its exclusive rights to any tiebreaker games that determine division or wild card champions.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] It also airs exclusive coverage of the Division Series round of the playoffs.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] TBS carries the League Championship Series that are not included under Fox's television agreement; TBS shows the NLCS in odd-numbered years and the ALCS in even-numbered years.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In January 2009, MLB launched MLB Network, featuring news and coverage from around the league, and airing 26 live games in the 2009 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Each team also has local broadcasts for all games not exclusively carried nationally.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] These games are typically split between a local broadcast television station and a local or regional sports network (RSN), though some teams only air local games through RSNs or through their own team networks.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] As Canada only contains one team, Sportsnet broadcasts Toronto Blue Jays games nationally.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The channel is owned by Rogers Communications, who is also the parent company of the Blue Jays.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Sportsnet also televises Fox's Saturday afternoon games, the All-Star Game, playoff games, and the World Series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In April 2011, TSN2 began carrying ESPN *Sunday Night Baseball* in Canada.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] TVA Sports airs Blue Jays games in French.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Several MLB games are broadcast exclusively on streaming television.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] After a year of exclusive games on Facebook, MLB partnered with YouTube to stream weekly games on the service beginning in the 2019 season, and extending until 2022.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2022, MLB made a deal with Apple Inc. to launch *Friday Night Baseball* on its Apple TV+ streaming service, and NBC Sports to broadcast *MLB Sunday Leadoff*, a package of early Sunday afternoon games on Peacock.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Since the 2023 season's Division Series, HBO Max began simulcasting games broadcast by its sister network TBS (both owned by Warner Bros.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In the 2024 season, The Roku Channel began streaming *MLB Sunday Leadoff*.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Announced in November 2025, MLB signed three-year media-rights deals with Netflix, ESPN, and NBCUniversal for the 2026 to 2028 seasons.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] A local broadcaster has priority to televise games of the team in their market over national broadcasters if the game is not exclusive to the national broadcaster.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] A market that has a local team playing in a non-exclusive game will receive an alternative programming feed on the national broadcaster.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] MLB's streaming internet video service is also subject to the same blackout rules.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Commissioner Robert Manfred has expressed interest in changing the blackout policy to loosen the rules for streaming options.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The first baseball game ever broadcast on radio was a Pittsburgh Pirates versus Philadelphia Phillies game on August 5, 1921.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The game was broadcast by KDKA of Pittsburgh, and the Pirates defeated the Phillies 8–5.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] It was broadcast by KDKA staff announcer Harold Arlin.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] That year, KDKA and WJZ of Newark broadcast the first World Series on the radio, between the New York Giants and the New York Yankees, with Grantland Rice and Tommy Cowan calling the games for KDKA and WJZ, respectively.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] However, the broadcasters were not actually present at the game, but simply gave reports from a telegraph wire.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In 1922, WJZ broadcast the entire series, with Rice doing play-by-play.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] For the 1923 World Series, Rice was joined on Westinghouse for the first time by Graham McNamee.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] During the 1923 World Series, Rice was the main broadcaster, but during the fourth inning of Game 3, he turned the microphone over to McNamee.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] This was the start of McNamee's career, and McNamee became the first color commentator.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Although frequently criticized for his lack of expertise, McNamee helped popularize baseball.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In 1998, national radio broadcasts moved to ESPN Radio.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] ESPN Radio currently broadcasts *Sunday Night Baseball* games during the regular season, as well as Saturday and occasional weekday games, along with the All-Star Game and all postseason contests.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2021, TUDN Radio airs Spanish-language coverage of select regular season and postseason games, including the World Series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In addition, each team employs its own announcers, who broadcast during the regular season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Most teams operate regional networks to cover their fan bases; some of these supposedly regional networks (such as the New York Yankees Radio Network) have a national reach with affiliates located across the United States.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Major League Baseball has an exclusive rights deal with XM Satellite Radio, which includes the channel MLB Network Radio and live play-by-play of all games.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] MLB games are also broadcast live on the internet.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] All television and radio broadcasts of games are available via subscription to MLB.tv at Major League Baseball's website, MLB.com, and radio-only broadcasts are also available via subscription to MLB.com Gameday Audio.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2026, MLB.tv will be integrated into the ESPN App.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2005, Major League Baseball has a partnership with XM Satellite Radio, launching a 24-7 channel, MLB Home Plate (now MLB Network Radio) which carries every major league game.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Games are also carried on MLB Gameday Audio.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] While all teams maintain a network of stations carrying their games in English, many teams also broadcast their games in Spanish, on a second network.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In addition, when the Washington Nationals were based in Montreal as the Montreal Expos, their games were broadcast in both English and French.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Some Toronto Blue Jays games have been broadcast in French as well.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Selected games of the Los Angeles Dodgers are broadcast in Korean by KMPC.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In modern years, teams have become increasingly reliant on local cable television rights fees, which grew unstable in the 2020s and which are not subject to equal revenue sharing.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Following the Disney-Fox merger, Disney divested Fox's regional broadcasting networks, which covered 14 of MLB's 30 teams, to Diamond Sports Network / Bally Sports.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Diamond filed for bankruptcy in 2023 and took advantage of debtor-friendly rules in the Bankruptcy Code to cancel or renegotiate its TV deals with a third of the league.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Teams that locked themselves into relatively stable deals near the peak of the market found themselves in a stronger financial position relative to the average team than ever before.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Critics respond that industry revenues and team valuations are still rising.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] ESPN broadcasts some MLB games in other countries, including ESPN Australia in Australia and New Zealand, ESPN Africa, and ESPN in the Netherlands.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In Mexico, until 2022, Fox Sports aired five regular season games per week and post-season games that belong to the league that broadcasts its American namesake (including the Wild Card Series).
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Likewise, TUDN carried 4 matches a week until 2022: through the pay television signal, games were broadcast on Tuesdays and Thursdays, while on Saturdays (generally at 12:00 p.m.) and Sundays (rotating between NBA games, until the start of the NFL season) games were broadcast on Canal 9.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting with the Championship Series, it only broadcast one division and the whole World Series, these were broadcast on free-to-air television for 59 years.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting with the 2023 season, Imagen Televisión announced it would begin broadcasting a regular season game every Saturday and Sunday as well as the playoffs and the World Series on open television and its website in Mexico.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In Argentina, Fox Sports carries 5 regular season games per week and post-season games that belong to the league that broadcasts its American namesake (including the Wild Card Series).
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In Venezuela, since the 2016 season the cable channel IVC has the broadcast rights, they currently air 7 games per week.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting with the 2022 season, Televen broadcasts two games a week and the postseason on free-to-air TV While Venevisión, starting with the 2023 season, would return with the space "El Juego de la Semana" that carries a game every Sunday and non-working days on free-to-air television.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In the Dominican Republic since 2009 Grupo Altice has broadcast the entire regular season, playoffs and World Series through pay TV while on free-to-air television and radio Grupo Corripio airs 7 games per week and the entire postseason.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In Spain, Movistar Plus+ has the rights to broadcast the entire season, including one game daily, and the postseason, covering all games in the championship series and World Series.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Channel 5 in the United Kingdom previously screened MLB games, including the All-Star Game and postseason games, on Sunday and Wednesday, usually starting at 1 a.m.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Most recently, Johnny Gould and Josh Chetwynd presented *MLB on Five* on that station.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] The channel covered baseball beginning on its opening night in 1997, but for financial reasons, the decision was made not to pick up MLB for the 2009 season.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] BT Sport ESPN show live and recorded games several times a week—it is available with BT Sport and (on a subscriber-basis) Virgin Media in the UK.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] ESPN America televised many games in the UK and dozens of other countries; in May 2013, ESPN announced that it would shut down the channel on July 31, 2013.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In the Middle East, North Africa and France, MLB games are broadcast on beIN Sports channels.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] In Germany, Austria and Switzerland, as many as 500 MLB games will be broadcast from 2022 exclusively on the Sport1 platforms until 2026.
[src:major-league-baseball/major-league-baseball-p02] Sport1 also broadcasts MLB games in Hungary, as of 2025.
